{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"930728e4-bfdf-4a3e-a4fe-a65baadc4867","content":"\n\nUse conditional compilation with `#if` directives in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Place each platform implementation under `Platforms/<Platform>/` — those folders already have the correct build targets.\n- `ANDROID`, `IOS`, and `WINDOWS` are predefined symbols set by the MAUI SDK per target framework.\n- Only the relevant registration compiles for each platform, so there's no risk of missing type references at runtime.\n- Inject `INotificationService` via constructor injection anywhere you need it.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1c97d9ae-ecf9-4a75-878c-12a71fd0a9d9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection setup for platform-specific services. This is a general knowledge question — no codebase exploration needed.","outputTokens":328},"id":"e906122d-1166-42d5-926c-4f2f237c7e28","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:39:14.856Z","parentId":"9a791b1e-b94f-43fc-9c75-a2b1a834a854"}
